I came to find out that it is a combination of the two, and then some.  The have all kinds of assortments to include coffee, cakes, pies, and even regular lunch type of food.  I noticed tueprkeu and swiss wraps, cold cut croissant sandwiches, and pasta dishes.  I went for the chicken kabob lunch platter. This could become a gem if it was better managed as a business. They know what they are doing in the bakery side and excel at that, but the place is not particularly inviting, and it's clear they are not familiar w category management. The space, particularly the entrance and counter, is crammed w fridges and shelves selling you anything under the sun: Energy supplements, premade food, pretzles. This all dilutes who they are. Is it a bakery or a deli w cakes? In a busy weekend morning the line hits the door immediately and getting to the tiny counter to get your food is a challenge. The tables and furniture also look dated and feel crammed. I would recommend then to watch Alex Polizzi's show in YouTube  "the fixer" - multiple examples of the same problem. If feel if they change things they could become a destination.

This place's food is ok.  Sometimes I go there in the mornings for coffee if I happen to run out at home.  The coffee you get here is way overpriced for the meh quality you get.  In fact a lot of things are overpriced there as well...approximately 25% more than other stores.  Also, I've purchased a pecan pie here. It might have been because it was close to Thanksgiving but it cost $35.  That's borderline criminal like when Texas gas stations jacked up prices due to the hurricanes that hit a few years ago. If it's $35 normally, that's fine... But I wouldn't pay that when I can make one for about 5... I was in a pinch so I had to at that time. Anyway, if you don't mind the rate hikes, go here... In the end the food is still just ok and you'll get way less than what you paid for.

From grand opening till now, what was it? 7 years? 8? I've been coming to these guys like you would to Sunday Mass (or Friday Namaz) (or Saturday Shul) (we're inclusive here). Most bakeries would begin shorting the sugar, balking the wheat, cheating the yeast, but not these guys. These guys brought their French knowhow to the game. Closest thing to a real pain au raisin or chocolatine you can get this side of the Atlantic (as far as I remember it in Nimes, junior year abroad). Very nice "your neighborhood bakery" charm. Columbia Heights's pick for weekly bread, or Sunday coffee. Nothing like it in DC, or at the very least, or neck of the woods. Protip: Some less-favored menu stars are the pistachio and almond cookies, as well as the apple and blueberry scones.

Having worked here, and shopped here, I can say two things;  This bakery is truly French. The owners themselves are French, and they will carry traditional French seasonal baked goods as well as other classics. They do hot meals, cookies by the pound, grab 'n' go meals, all sorts of drinks, gelato, soups, cakes, cake decorations, catering and probably hundreds of other things. Their easter treats are to die for!  You get a french cafe vibe, and will not be pressured to leave. The outside seating is a hot commodity in the summer, so you may get dirty looks from patrons, but never staff.  Pets are welcome in outside seat areas, and families are always welcomed.

They pointed out one last measly little piece, sitting right by the checkout. I asked if they had other vegan treats and they said they had a scone. I got a weird vibe from both that they either thought I was a crazy vegan or that they hate their lives. I bought the carrot cake anyway. Sat down to eat it and had to go back up and ask for a fork, where they looked at me again like I was a weirdo. Bad vibes, cake was overly sweet and not worth a trip back.
